observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management

(a) direct the Property Officer and the Municipal Accountant to properly maintain, regularly update and reconcile their respective subsidiary records on PPE and inventory supplies;

(b) prepare an updated inventory report of the buildings and other infrastructures for submission to the Auditor;

(c) require the Municipal Accountant to exert effort to locate the pertinent documents that would show the details of the unaccounted balances and to establish the accuracy of the PPE balances; and

(d) ensure that all PPE acquisitions and completed infrastructure projects of the Municipality are recorded in the books of accounts.

We recommended that Management
(a) make representations with the National Solid Waste Management Commission to follow-up or monitor the status on the approval of the re-WACS;
(b) implement fully and efficiently the SWMP and its updates for an effective solid waste management.

We recommended that Management

(a) maximize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund for projects that are permanent in nature in order to best serve the Municipality’s constituents;

(b) plan and strictly implement all projects in accordance with the provisions of DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017; and (c) require the posting of appropriate project signboards and or public notices before the start of the program or activity in order to attain transparency, efficiency and effectiveness in the utilization and implementation of the fund.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that Members of the City Local School Board:

(a) request for inputs from the Deped official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund; 

(b) prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute; 

(c) ensure that Programs, Projects and Activities (PPAs) are in accordance with the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund; 

(d) stop granting cash advances to non-employees of the city government; and 

submit a written explanation and justification on why those expenditures were charged to the fund.

We recommended that the Municipal Government:

(a) strictly comply with   the provisions of the annual General Provisions of GAA regarding the allowable net take home pay per month of government employees; 

(b) adopt policies and internal controls in processing of payroll and issuance of Certificate of Net Pay; 

(c) direct the Human Resource Management Office to require the submission of an accomplishment report of job orders, casuals and consultants every month together with the approved DTR; and 

(d) install tighter internal control of its payroll funds for casual and job order employees by using the automated teller machine (ATM) payroll system.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to 

(a) account for the deficiencies noted in the amount withheld and amount actually remitted, including errors or deficiencies in the beginning balance; 

(b) establish an internal separate subsidiary ledger for the current year’s correct and duly accounted for Due to BIR account and another one for the balance that is still subject to reconciliation; 

(c)  invariably remit in full all withheld taxes within the prescribed period to avoid the penalties from non-compliance with BIR regulation; and 

(d) exert efforts to clear the books from the erroneous entries in the Due to BIR account  through review of past entries and records and coordination with the BIR, as warranted by the situation.

